{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17534957","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17534957"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:51:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:51:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15237"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15237"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.01,0.02,0.12,0.84]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7928"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60726"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7928"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15237"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46154"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"118"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1387"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19319"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60726"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of right-sided facial weakness and tinnitus. She reports a burning sensation in her right ear followed by the appearance of small blisters. She had Bell\u0027s palsy after delivery of her first child 40 years ago, has diabetes mellitus and metformin only. She denies any trauma or new lotions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are grouped vesicles and crust in the right external auditory canal and on the right pinna. She has right-sided facial weakness involving the forehead and mouth. Her right eye cannot fully close. Otoscopic examination reveals vesicles on the right tympanic membrane.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cerebral vascular event","Bacterial otitis externa","Bell palsy","Herpes simplex infection","Ramsay Hunt syndrome"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of Ramsay Hunt syndrome: facial nerve palsy, otalgia, and vesicles in the external auditory canal. The condition is caused by reactivation of \u003Cem\u003EVaricella zoster virus\u003C/em\u003E in the geniculate ganglion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERamsay Hunt syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E typically affects older adults and has a worse prognosis than Bell palsy if not treated promptly with antivirals within 72 hours of the onset of symptoms. The presence of vesicles in the ear distinguishes it from Bell palsy.  Strict control of her diabetes is important as diabetes mellitus has a negative prognostic factor, as well as advanced age, essential hypertension and vertigo.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBell palsy\u003C/strong\u003E presents with acute unilateral facial weakness but does not involve vesicular lesions or severe ear pain. While it is more common than Ramsay Hunt syndrome, the presence of vesicles makes it unlikely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex infection\u003C/strong\u003E can cause vesicles but rarely causes facial nerve palsy. When it does affect the facial nerve, the vesicles typically appear around the mouth rather than in the ear, and would not cause facial paralysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial otitis externa\u003C/strong\u003E causes ear pain and can present with discharge, but does not cause facial weakness or vesicular lesions. The ear canal would typically be erythematous and swollen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebral vascular event\u003C/strong\u003E can cause facial weakness but typically presents with other neurological signs and would not explain the vesicular rash or ear pain. Additionally, in stroke, forehead sparing is typical due to bilateral upper motor neuron innervation, unlike this case where the forehead is involved.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ramsay Hunt syndrome presents with facial nerve palsy and vesicular rash in the external ear or tongue."],"references":["Yeo SW, Lee DH, Jun BC, Chang KH, Park YS. Analysis of prognostic factors in Bell\u0027s palsy and Ramsay Hunt syndrome. Auris Nasus Larynx. 2007 Jun;34(2):159-64.  Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17055202/","Yeong S, Tassone P.  Acute unilateral facial nerve palsy.  Australian Family Physcian. 2011: 40 (5).  Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/bc2a8d1f-1213-4837-8f58-6ee228b62504/Acute-unilateral-facial-nerve-palsy.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46154"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15237"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"46154","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/46154"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-13T22:51:31+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-13T22:52:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7928"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60726"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":nul